s not directly overlap with that of the storytelling perspective.Through rigorous analysis of novels and short fiction, such as Sesshu Foster’s Atomik Aztex, Sabina Murray’s A Carnivore’s Inquiry and Sigrid Nunez’s The Last of Her Kind, Sohn reveals how the construction of narrative perspective allows the Asian American writer a flexible aesthetic canvas upon which to engage issues of oppression and inequity, power and subjectivity, and the complicated construction of racial identity. Speaking to concerns running through postcolonial studies and American literature at large, Racial Asymmetries employs an interdisciplinary approach to reveal the unbounded nature of fictional worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexAsian American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEquality in literature. 0aFirst person narrativexHistory and criticism. 0aPoint of view (Literature). 0aRace in literature. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107289960 cprintz978147980007040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479800070.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479800551423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479800551/original  a978-3-11-072899-6  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK